issue.body:
## Description
I want to implement a feature that automatically posts a message whenever a Pull Request (PR) is created by any contributor.  

This workflow will make the PR process more **reliable and efficient**, and it will guide contributors to double-check important things in their PRs, so they can modify them before review.  

I have attached a screenshot showing what the comment message should look like.

## Benefits
- Contributors immediately see guidance on what needs to be checked.
- Reduces common mistakes in PRs.
- Makes the review process faster and smoother.

## Proposed Workflow
- **Trigger:** When a PR is opened (`pull_request` event).  
- **Action:** Automatically post a comment message to the PR.

## Example Comment Message
>Thanks for creating a PR for your Issue! ‚ò∫Ô∏è

>We'll review it as soon as possible.
>In the meantime, please double-check the file changes and ensure that all commits are accurate.

>If there are any unresolved review comments, feel free to resolve them. üôåüèº


---------
Please assign this issue to me and add `GSSOC'25` and appropriate `level` labels.

issue.title: Panic when deleting inside bracket matcher with syntax highlighting enabled
issue.body:
## Description
When using `rustyline` with syntax highlighting (bracket matcher), deleting last characters before closing brackets can cause a panic.

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Run a program using `rustyline` with syntax highlighting enabled (e.g., with `MatchingBracketHighlighter`).
2. Type the following into the console: `[1 2 3]`
3. Place the cursor after the `3`.
4. Press backspace once -> removes `3`.
5. Press backspace again -> **panic occurs**.

## Observed behavior
```
[1 2 ]
thread 'main' panicked at /home/USERNAME/.cargo/registry/src/index.crates.io-1949cf8c6b5b557f/rustyline-17.0.0/src/highlight.rs:143:37:
range end index 6 out of range for slice of length 5
note: run with RUST_BACKTRACE=1 environment variable to display a backtrace
```

## Environment
- `rustyline` version: 17.0.0
- Rust version: 1.88
- OS: Fedora

## Additional context
It seems the issue is caused by the bracket matching logic calculating a range past the end of the current line buffer after deletion.

pull_request.body:
This PR updates the drone registry data model and user interface to use more precise units for better data accuracy and consistency across the application.

## Changes Made

### Unit Conversions
- **Operating Time**: hours ‚Üí minutes (more precise for flight operations)
- **Range**: kilometers ‚Üí meters (better precision for UAV specifications)
- **Weight & Max Takeoff Weight**: kilograms ‚Üí grams (standard for small UAV specs)
- **Dimensions** (length, width, height): centimeters ‚Üí millimeters (manufacturing precision)

### Files Updated

**Data Model (`types/Drone.ts`)**
- Updated interface comments to reflect new units
- All affected fields now use more precise unit specifications

**Forms (`app/drone-form.tsx`)**
- Updated all input labels and placeholders
- Changed weight inputs from `parseFloat` to `parseInt` for whole number units
- Form validation now expects values in new units

**Display Components (`app/drone-details.tsx`, `app/drones-list.tsx`)**
- Updated display text to show new units
- Integrated smart formatting functions for better readability

**Service Layer (`services/droneService.ts`)**
- Added comprehensive formatting utilities:
  - `formatOperatingTime()` - displays "35 minutes" or "1 hours 15 minutes"
  - `formatWeight()` - displays "895g" or "1.2kg (1200g)" for readability
  - `formatRange()` - displays "500m" or "1.5km (1500m)" for context
  - `formatDimensions()` - displays "221 x 96 x 90 mm" or includes cm for larger values

**Documentation (`DRONE_REGISTRY_IMPLEMENTATION.md`)**
- Updated to reflect new unit specifications
- Enhanced Firebase collection schema documentation

## User Experience Improvements

The new formatting functions provide context-aware display:

```typescript
// Before: "1.25h", "2.5km", "1.2kg", "25cm"
// After: "1 hours 15 minutes", "2.5km (2500m)", "1.2kg (1200g)", "25.0cm (250mm)"
```

## Backward Compatibility

The changes are designed to handle existing data gracefully:
- Forms now expect input in new units
- Display components show values with appropriate formatting
- No database migration required - new data uses precise units while maintaining display clarity

## Testing

- Comprehensive validation confirms all unit changes are consistent across files
- Integration tests verify the complete workflow from form input to display
- All TypeScript interfaces and React components properly handle the new unit specifications

This update significantly improves the precision and usability of drone specifications while maintaining excellent user experience through smart formatting.

[JSC] `WebAssembly.JSTag` should be cached
https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=297126

Reviewed by NOBODY (OOPS!).

According to the specification [1][2], objects created by `WebAssembly.JSTag`
should be stored in the Tag object cache. So, when `WebAssembly.JSTag` is called
multiple times, they should return the same object. However, the current JSC
does not behave this way.

This patch changes `JSGlobalObject` to cache `JSTag`.

issue.title: 16Kb Page Size Support
issue.body:
The native library arm64-v8a/libmupdf_java.so is currently not aligned to a 16 KB boundary. While Android has traditionally used 4 KB page sizes, newer devices are moving to 16 KB pages. For an app to run on these future devices, its uncompressed native libraries must be 16 KB aligned.

You can find Google's official documentation on this requirement here: [Support 16 KB page sizes](https://www.google.com/search?q=https://developer.android.com/about/versions/15/features/16k-page-size-support%23native-libraries-must-be-16k-aligned).

pull_request.body:
#### d780190fc900264e67550b162e885350eb4f1c4a 
[JSC] `WebAssembly.JSTag` should be cached
https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=297126

Reviewed by NOBODY (OOPS!).

According to the specification [1][2], objects created by `WebAssembly.JSTag`
should be stored in the Tag object cache. So, when `WebAssembly.JSTag` is called
multiple times, they should return the same object. However, the current JSC
does not behave this way.

This patch changes `JSGlobalObject` to cache `JSTag`.

issue.body:
### Issue: Inability to Connect Sunshine Server to Samsung TV After Latest Prerelease Update

**Description:**
After updating my Sunshine server to the latest prerelease version [v2025.306.40944](https://github.com/LizardByte/Sunshine/releases/tag/v2025.306.40944), I encountered an issue where I was no longer able to connect to the server from my Samsung TV. However, all other clients (Android, Linux) continued to work fine.

**Steps Taken:**
1. Updated Sunshine server to [v2025.306.40944](https://github.com/LizardByte/Sunshine/releases/tag/v2025.306.40944).
2. Attempted to connect from Samsung TV - Connection failed.
3. Verified connection from other clients (Android, Linux) - Connection successful.
4. Downgraded Sunshine server back to [v0.23.1](https://github.com/LizardByte/Sunshine/releases/tag/v0.23.1).
5. Verified connection from Samsung TV - Connection successful.

**Request for Help:**
- Is this a known problem with the latest prerelease?
- Could this issue be related to SSL libraries?
- How can I provide more information to help diagnose the issue?

**Environment:**
- Sunshine Server Version: v2025.306.40944 (Prerelease), v0.23.1 (Stable)
- Samsung TV Model: [Insert Model Here]
- Other Clients: Android, Linux
